image.altText: A designed image showing Malcolm Turnbull gesturing with his finger and Barnaby Joyce  looking downcast.

props.synopsis: The former merchant banker and bush accountant enjoyed an unlikely but successful political partnership. That all changed when Malcolm Turnbull strode into his courtyard and denounced Barnaby Joyce in front of the nation over his affair with a staffer, Vikki Campion.

title.children: The inside story of how an affair, a press conference and a 'bonk ban' blew up a political partnership

image.altText: A graphic showing a man coughing, a rapid antigen COVID test and three spike proteins

props.synopsis: Behind the scenes governments have been steadily dismantling many other elements of a surveillance system that we were so reliant on in the emergency period of the COVID-19 pandemic, writes Casey Briggs.

title.children: If you've tried to look up COVID cases recently, you'll have noticed something has changed

image.altText: A police officer stands by an escalator with blue and white police tap around it.

props.synopsis: Police are reviewing CCTV footage of the incident, which a detective described as "extremely confronting to watch", and calling for members of the public to come forward if they have any information.

title.children: Grandmother dies after being stabbed in the chest during 'abhorrent, cowardly' attack at shopping centre west of Brisbane

image.altText: Kate Selway working in glacial wind

props.synopsis: Kate Selway has spent the past two months battling subzero temperatures, perpetual sunlight, and getting stuck on the ice to help unlock the secrets of Antarctica’s melting glaciers.

title.children: Antarctica is one of the most remote places on Earth. This is what it’s like spend summer there

image.altText: A composite of a young blonde woman and a mugshot of the same woman

props.synopsis: Fifty years ago, a teenaged heiress with a famous last name was kidnapped from her California apartment by armed terrorists. What followed was one of the most confounding crimes in American history.

title.children: A teenaged heiress was kidnapped by American terrorists. Why did she grab a gun and join them?

image.altText: Tom Gleeson standing with his arms crossed with a serious look on his face with th Hard quiz logo in the top left corner

props.synopsis: So, you think you're good at quizzes but don't have the guts to front up to my actual TV show? Well, try this then.

title.children: Hard Quiz: You better believe I'm here to judge you. Let's play HARD!

image.altText: Michele Bullock in corridor.

props.synopsis: A raft of official economic data suggests Australia's economy suddenly hit a wall in December. Is the data wrong, or did the Reserve Bank raise rates one time too many in November?

title.children: A rate cut in May is not only possible, it may prove to be too little, too late

image.altText: Joko Widido left shakes hands with a crowd of supporters next to his son who is also greeting people.

props.synopsis: Less than a fortnight out from Indonesia's election, President Joko Widodo's son is proving to be the decisive factor driving some of the country's almost 200 million voters towards his joint ticket. Could he secure the Widodo political dynasty?

title.children: Joko Widodo can't run for election again, but Indonesia's voters hope his son will carry on his legacy

image.altText: Two women stand in a parliamentary lobby wearing semi-formal attire, smiling.

props.synopsis: Jude Hudson was whisked away to give birth in a home for unwed mothers in her mid-teens, then her baby girl was taken from her. She may now be entitled to compensation for Victorian mothers forced to put their children up for adoption.

title.children: Mother separated from daughter for 18 years among first to apply for Australian-first redress scheme

image.altText: A group of children hold out empty pots and containers.

props.synopsis: Signs of a Hamas resurgence in the Gaza Strip's largest city underscore the group's resilience despite Israel's deadly air and ground campaign against it over the past four months.

title.children: Hamas deploys police forces, makes payments to civil servants in Gaza City

image.altText: A group of US soldiers in camouflage uniform carry a flag-draped metal case out of an airplane.

props.synopsis: The US military says the US carried out retaliatory air strikes in Iraq and Syria against more than 85 targets linked to Iran's Revolutionary Guard and the militias they back.

title.children: 'If you harm an American, we will respond': US conducts strikes in Iraq and Syria, killing 39

image.altText: A silhouette stature of a man holding a spear in front of a sunset.

props.synopsis: John Pat's death at just 16 inside an outback police lock-up sparked national outrage and a royal commission. Forty years later, what is his legacy in his hometown?

title.children: 'Blood has been spilled': Stain of distrust lingers four decades after death of Aboriginal teen John Pat

image.altText: Farmer Bill Mott, wearing a hat, sits in a chair in a shed while being interviewed by Daniel Ziffer.

props.synopsis: The issues that led to the royal commission five years ago have faded, even if they haven't all been fixed. As new issues like scams and the impact of artificial intelligence capture attention, advocates want banks to keep a focus on doing the right thing by their customers.

title.children: Five years since the final report of the banking royal commission, are ordinary customers better off?

image.altText: A man in a blue shirt and vest sits next to a woman in dark black conservative Islamic garb behind a table.

props.synopsis: A Pakistan court has sentenced former prime minister Imran Khan to a further seven years in prison along with his wife, after a ruling that their 2018 marriage violated the law.

title.children: Former Pakistan PM Imran Khan and his wife get seven-year sentences for unlawful marriage

image.altText: A young female wrestler wearing a red and black bodysuit had another female wrestler in a headlock.

props.synopsis: Nethmi Poruthotage's coach had to pawn his gold necklace to help her compete at the 2022 Commonwealth Games. Now she's hoping to pay him back in Paris.

title.children: The teenage Sri Lankan wrestling sensation who's given up everything to chase her dreams

image.altText: Two-storey white house.

props.synopsis: If you're buying a home that has been "substantially renovated" you may have to pay GST. The problem home buyers face is that what qualifies as a "substantial renovation" is uncertain, writes Christine Peacock.

title.children: Buying a renovated home? You could be up for an extra 10 per cent GST, but it's a grey area

image.altText: Megan Schutt's teammates gather around her to celebrate a wicket

props.synopsis: Australian quick Megan Schutt celebrates her milestone match with a miserly spell in an eight-wicket thumping of South Africa in the series-opening women's one-day international.

title.children: Australia cruises to victory over South Africa in first ODI in Adelaide

image.altText: dean carelse SA team

props.synopsis: A basic internet search that would have revealed the criminal convictions of paedophile Dean Carelse was never done when he was screened for a job as a children's lifeguard at a UK family fun park, the ABC has confirmed.

title.children: A Google search would have revealed paedophile's past offences before he got lifeguard job – but nobody did one

image.altText: A young woman stands next to a batch of jars filled with tallow products.

props.synopsis: It started as a war-time snack that reduced waste during food scarcity, but now tallow is making Australia one of the most significant players in biofuel exports.

title.children: From dripping on bread to biofuels and skincare, demand for tallow is surging

image.altText: Police investigate in a suburban street.

props.synopsis: South Australia Police says a mother and son have been found dead at a home at Rosewater in Adelaide's north-west. A 43-year-old man who lived in the same street has been arrested.

title.children: Man arrested following alleged murder of mother and son in Adelaide's north-west

image.altText: White capped waves roll towards the white sand that's surrounded by greenery under a deep blue sky.

props.synopsis: Crashing waves, beautiful boulders, emus and wombats help Squeaky Beach take out top spot on Australia's Top 10 best beaches.

title.children: 'It could be a painting': Victorian beach named the best in Australia

image.altText: Anonymised pic of a doctor's hands at a desk holding a stethoscope

props.synopsis: Hannah achieved her dream of becoming a doctor — but she says it's come at a great cost due to the traumatic discrimination she's faced.

title.children: This doctor says ableism has hindered her career in medicine, and she wants the stigma to end

image.altText: A woman sits in a chair outside with a glass of champagne in her hands

props.synopsis: Catherina van der Linden died on Australia Day at Southern Cross Care's West Beach Residential Care home surrounded by her family. Her body will be donated to the University of Adelaide's Body Donation Program.

title.children: South Australian woman, believed to be Australia's oldest person, dies aged 111

image.altText: Luay Sako leaves a prison van, dressed in grey clothing.

props.synopsis: More than three years on, the family of Celeste Manno remain in disbelief that she was murdered by an intruder wielding a knife and a hammer in the middle of the night.

title.children: In a Melbourne court, the horror of 'bogeyman' killer Luay Sako's crime was laid bare

image.altText: A flooded street with a pub in the foreground

props.synopsis: If the tropical low develops into a cyclone, it would be Queensland's third in as many months.

title.children: Tropical low in Coral Sea could turn into cyclone as Kirrily hovers over Queensland's north-west

image.altText: A young woman in surf life saving uniform on the a sunny beach while holding a club board

props.synopsis: By letting volunteers choose their rostered hours, a NSW surf life saving club has almost quadrupled its patrolling members, setting an example other clubs are now following.

title.children: Struggling to mount beach patrols, surf club's simple idea brings volunteers flooding back

image.altText: cloud over mountain

props.synopsis: Take a climb up a peak in the early hours of the morning and you might be able to see a huge wave of white fog streaming down a cliff face. What causes these "cloud waterfalls" and how do you catch them?

title.children: Perfect conditions trigger rare 'cloud waterfall' in WA

image.altText: A group of people standing on the private charter boat "Waltzing Matilda"

props.synopsis: An environmental advocate says the changing climate means its more important than ever to protect the reef from human damage. It comes after a private charter skipper is convicted of numerous maritime offences.

title.children: Fears for health of Great Barrier Reef as skipper fined $15K over 21st birthday boat crash

image.altText: Composite of heatwave map and workers from Queensland Fire and Emergency Services

props.synopsis: A burst of hot northerly winds will bring the highest temperatures in years to parts of south-east Australia, while ex-Tropical Cyclone Kirrily carves a trail of torrential rain and flooding.

title.children: Parts of South Australia, Victoria, NSW to experience hottest weather in up to three years

image.altText: An 18-year-old female sprinter crosses the line in first place, with a smile, wearing a top and sprinting shorts.

props.synopsis: Fresh from setting the Australian record, 19-year-old Torrie Lewis is hopeful she can run even faster as she chases a qualifying time for the Paris Olympics.

title.children: Sprint star Lewis riding wave of confidence after breaking national 100m record

image.altText: Alysha Koloi shows of her gold medal at the 2024 World Aquatics Championships.

props.synopsis: With the Paris Olympics on the horizon, Australia's Alysha Koloi claims victory at the world titles in Doha, winnings the women's one-metre springboard final.

title.children: Aussie Koloi dives to springboard gold at World Aquatics Championships
